http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Psychology is a social studies elective course that introduces students to the science of behavior and mental processes. It includes an overview of the history of psychology as well as an opportunity to study individual and social psychology and how the knowledge and methods of psychologists are applied to the solution of human problems. The content of this course includes human development; biological bases of behavior; sensation and perception; learning, memory, and cognition; behavior patterns; and psychological disorders and their treatments.
Perspectives and Research
Students will analyze the evolving nature of psychology as a social science.
Analyze developments in the field of psychology
Compare and contrast contemporary perspectives used by psychologists
Students will analyze the methods and measurements used to study behavior and mental processes.
Analyze methods for collecting data in the field of psychology
Evaluate the impact of American Psychological Association (APA) and federal guidelines on the ethical treatment of human and nonhuman research participants
Biology and Behaviors
Students will evaluate the behaviors related to sensation, perception, and consciousness.
Analyze how the processes of sensation and perception influence experiences and expectations in one's environment
Compare and contrast different stages of consciousness
Students will analyze how biology influences psychology.
Explain the effects of the brain, nervous system, and endocrine system on behavior
Analyze interactions between biological factors and life experiences and their influences on behavior
Conditioning, Learning, and Cognition
Students will analyze cognitive, moral, and social development throughout the human lifespan.
Explain how lifespan development influences behavior and human interactions
Evaluate the methods of conditioning and learning theories
Evaluate biological processes and disorders associated with memory
Analyze the development of intelligence
Dysfunctional Behaviors
Students will evaluate the impact of psychological disorders.
Compare and contrast various psychological disorders and treatments
Analyze various effects of psychological disorders on the individual, family, and society from multiple perspectives
